{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_30","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -L --fail --silent 'https://www.ebi.ac.uk/europepmc/webservices/rest/search?query=EXT_ID:15292201%20AND%20SRC:MED&format=json&resultType=core&pageSize=1'\"","aggregated_output":"{\"version\":\"6.9\",\"hitCount\":1,\"request\":{\"queryString\":\"EXT_ID:15292201 AND SRC:MED\",\"internalQuery\":\"EXT_ID:15292201 AND SRC:MED\",\"resultType\":\"CORE\",\"cursorMark\":\"*\",\"pageSize\":1,\"sort\":\"\",\"synonym\":false},\"resultList\":{\"result\":[{\"id\":\"15292201\",\"source\":\"MED\",\"pmid\":\"15292201\",\"doi\":\"10.1074/jbc.m402264200\",\"title\":\"Sec15 is an effector for the Rab11 GTPase in mammalian cells.\",\"authorString\":\"Zhang XM, Ellis S, Sriratana A, Mitchell CA, Rowe T.\",\"authorList\":{\"author\":[{\"fullName\":\"Zhang XM\",\"firstName\":\"Xiang-Ming\",\"lastName\":\"Zhang\",\"initials\":\"XM\",\"authorAffiliationDetailsList\":{\"authorAffiliation\":[{\"affiliation\":\"Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology, Monash University, Clayton, Victoria 3800, Australia.\"}]}},{\"fullName\":\"Ellis S\",\"firstName\":\"Sarah\",\"lastName\":\"Ellis\",\"initials\":\"S\",\"authorId\":{\"type\":\"ORCID\",\"value\":\"0000-0002-5772-6051\"}},{\"fullName\":\"Sriratana A\",\"firstName\":\"Absorn\",\"lastName\":\"Sriratana\",\"initials\":\"A\"},{\"fullName\":\"Mitchell CA\",\"firstName\":\"Christina A\",\"lastName\":\"Mitchell\",\"initials\":\"CA\",\"authorId\":{\"type\":\"ORCID\",\"value\":\"0000-0001-9372-3192\"}},{\"fullName\":\"Rowe T\",\"firstName\":\"Tony\",\"lastName\":\"Rowe\",\"initials\":\"T\"}]},\"authorIdList\":{\"authorId\":[{\"type\":\"ORCID\",\"value\":\"0000-0001-9372-3192\"},{\"type\":\"ORCID\",\"value\":\"0000-0002-5772-6051\"}]},\"dataLinksTagsList\":{\"dataLinkstag\":[\"altmetrics\",\"related_data\",\"wikipedia\"]},\"journalInfo\":{\"issue\":\"41\",\"volume\":\"279\",\"journalIssueId\":1203965,\"dateOfPublication\":\"2004 Oct\",\"monthOfPublication\":10,\"yearOfPublication\":2004,\"printPublicationDate\":\"2004-10-01\",\"journal\":{\"title\":\"The Journal of biological chemistry\",\"medlineAbbreviation\":\"J Biol Chem\",\"isoabbreviation\":\"J Biol Chem\",\"nlmid\":\"2985121R\",\"essn\":\"1083-351X\",\"issn\":\"0021-9258\"}},\"pubYear\":\"2004\",\"pageInfo\":\"43027-43034\",\"abstractText\":\"Rab/Ypt GTPases play key roles in the regulation of vesicular trafficking. They perform most of their functions in a GTP-bound form by interacting with specific downstream effectors. The exocyst is a complex of eight polypeptides involved in constitutive secretion and functions as an effector for multiple Ras-related small GTPases, including the Rab protein Sec4p in yeast. In this study, we have examined the localization and function of the Sec15 exocyst subunit in mammalian cells. Overexpressed Sec15 associated with clusters of tubular/vesicular elements that were concentrated in the perinuclear region. The tubular/vesicular clusters were dispersed throughout the cytoplasm upon treatment with the microtubule-depolymerizing agent nocodazole and were accessible to endocytosed transferrin, but not exocytic cargo (vesicular stomatitis virus glycoprotein). Consistent with these observations, Sec15 colocalized selectively with the recycling endosome marker Rab11 and exhibited a GTP-dependent interaction with the Rab11 GTPase, but not with Rab4, Rab6, or Rab7. These findings provide the first evidence that the exocyst functions as a Rab effector complex in mammalian cells.\",\"affiliation\":\"Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology, Monash University, Clayton, Victoria 3800, Australia.\",\"publicationStatus\":\"ppublish\",\"language\":\"eng\",\"pubModel\":\"Print-Electronic\",\"pubTypeList\":{\"pubType\":[\"Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't\",\"Journal Article\"]},\"meshHeadingList\":{\"meshHeading\":[{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Cell Line\"},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"COS Cells\"},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"CHO Cells\"},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Cell Membrane\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Cell Nucleus\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Cytoplasm\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Microtubules\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Endosomes\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Animals\"},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Humans\"},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"Nocodazole\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"PD\",\"qualifierName\":\"pharmacology\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"GTP-Binding Proteins\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"},{\"abbreviation\":\"CH\",\"qualifierName\":\"chemistry\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"Y\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"rab GTP-Binding Proteins\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbreviation\":\"ME\",\"qualifierName\":\"metabolism\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"Y\"},{\"abbreviation\":\"PH\",\"qualifierName\":\"physiology\",\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\"}]}},{\"majorTopic_YN\":\"N\",\"descriptorName\":\"rab4 GTP-Binding Proteins\",\"meshQualifierList\":{\"meshQualifier\":[{\"abbrevi